04673nam a22007935i 9781477307717DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212015txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773077177 a10.7560/3023782doi  a(DE-B1597)587114  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF1789.N3bS28 2016 7aSOC0080502bisacsh04a781.64/90972912231 aSaunders, Tanya L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCuban Underground Hip Hop :bBlack Thoughts, Black Revolution, Black Modernity /cTanya L. Saunders. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Historicizing Race, Cultural Politics, and Critical Music Cultures in Cuba -- t3. La Revolución dentro de la Revolución/ The Revolution within the Revolution -- t4. Whiteness, Mulat@ness, Blackness -- t5. “Never Has Anyone Spoken to You Like This” -- t6. “I’m a Feminist, But I Don’t Hate Men” -- t7. Kruda Knowledge, Kruda Discourse -- t8. Conclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the wake of the 1959 Cuban Revolution, a key state ideology developed: racism was a systemic cultural issue that ceased to exist after the Revolution, and any racism that did persist was a result of contained cases of individual prejudice perpetuated by US influence. Even after the state officially pronounced the end of racism within its borders, social inequalities tied to racism, sexism, and homophobia endured, and, during the economic liberalization of the 1990s, widespread economic disparities began to reemerge. Cuban Underground Hip Hop focuses on a group of self-described antiracist, revolutionary youth who initiated a social movement (1996–2006) to educate and fight against these inequalities through the use of arts-based political activism intended to spur debate and enact social change. Their “revolution” was manifest in altering individual and collective consciousness by critiquing nearly all aspects of social and economic life tied to colonial legacies. Using over a decade of research and interviews with those directly involved, Tanya L. Saunders traces the history of the movement from its inception and the national and international debates that it spawned to the exodus of these activists/artists from Cuba and the creative vacuum they left behind. Shedding light on identity politics, race, sexuality, and gender in Cuba and the Americas, Cuban Underground Hip Hop is a valuable case study of a social movement that is a part of Cuba’s longer historical process of decolonization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aBlacksxEthnic identityxCuba. 0aBlacksxEthnic identity. 0aBlacksxPolitical activityxCuba. 0aBlacksxPolitical activityzCuba. 0aBlacksxPolitical activity. 0aBlackszCubaxEthnic identity. 0aHip-hopxCuba. 0aHip-hopzCuba. 0aHip-hop. 0aMusicxPolitical aspectsxCuba. 0aMusicxPolitical aspectszCuba. 0aMusicxPolitical aspects. 0aRace relations. 0aRacismxCuba. 0aRacismzCuba. 0aRacism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Caribbean & Latin American Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/30237840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477307717423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477307717/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK